summary:
I am thrilled to be working as the Operations Manager at Stratosyst, an exciting startup in the higher airspace industry. 

At Stratosyst, we are dedicated to developing innovative High Altitude Platform Stations (HAPS) - wonder, what that is? 

Well...flying giants, that will provide you with internet access altough you are in the middle of a desert, can help with natural disasters, global warming, coast erosion or space monitoring and observation. 

As the Operations manager, my primary focus is to develop procedures that push the boundaries of what is possible in the field of higher airspace operations with these giants. My team and I are constantly brainstorming and collaborating to find new and unique ways to take our aircraft to new heights (quite literally!).

The journey ahead is an exciting one, and I invite you to join me and the rest of the Stratosyst team as we make history together. Buckle up, folks! #Stratosyst #HAPS #AerospaceEngineering

visit for more information: 

https://www.stratosyst.com/
https://hapsalliance.org/

projects:
[{'title': 'Application of Axiomatic Design in Engineering: Designing a Smart  Medical Cast Increasing robustness by decreasing information', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}, 'end': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2022}}, 'description': 'Abstract: Axiomatic Design was applied during the development of a Smart Medical Cast. This device provides patients, who suffer from forearm fractures, with a personalized healing process by monitoring the overall healing status and common complications. These complications are muscle atrophy, compartment syndrome, and deep vein thrombosis. In the conceptual phase, desk research has been performed to find biomarkers that correlate with the monitored processes. Per biomarker, a measuring principle has been designed and these combined formed the design of the smart medical cast. Following the design phase, two tests were performed on healthy individuals to measure the robustness in a real application. The first test focused on correctly measuring the biomarkers and further specifying the sensor specifications. For the second test, a new prototype was used to determine correlations between 
the measured data and the monitored process and the impact of application during the casting process. The test results show that the measuring system can measure the biomarkers within the expected range, except for bone density. No significant impact on the casting process was measured. The Smart Medical Cast has only been evaluated in situations without a fracture, the next step will be to test the measurables in an environment with a fracture.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': ' Jakub ', 'last_name': 'Kylar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Guiding students to reach new heights in careers & lives, while operating from Stratosphere ‚ú®üõ∞Ô∏è'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Lennard', 'last_name': 'Spauwen', 'name': None, 'headline': 'PhD student - UMC Utrecht | Researcher - Smart Systems for Healthy Living'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Tim', 'last_name': 'Heijne', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Ingenieur werktuigbouwkunde | Project ingenieur'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mitch', 'last_name': 'Kruijer', 'name': None, 'headline': 'MSc in Next Level Electrical Engineering'}]}, {'title': 'Virtual Comissioning of industrial machine development of digital twin and application of virtual commissioning methods (master thesis)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2022}, 'end': {'month': 8, 'day': None, 'year': 2022}}, 'description': "Thesis abstract: Implementing virtual validation methods within engineering companies is becoming more of a standard. Nowadays, tools are available to incorporate virtual machine validation on different levels. The system architecture is often simulated via various tools (such as Simulink and MATLAB). However, less known platforms such as Simcenter Amesim are trying to help companies in virtual commissioning (VC) of their products. However, there is a lack of information on what materials must be gathered and how the Simcenter Amesim should be incorporated within companies' procedures. This research focused on building a digital twin of the industrial machine ‚Äì Rootshoot phenotyper to find eventual bottlenecks within the commissioning process. This was assessed via testing the Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) coupling with the Amesim model of a Rootshoot phenotyper. The research found that to commission automation code with a Simcenter Amesim, PLC code must be programmed simultaneously with creating a Simcenter Amesim model of the corresponding machine. Besides this assessment, a conceptual framework for VC was designed to help SMO standardize VC procedure and apply that in a product development cycle.", 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': ' Jakub ', 'last_name': 'Kylar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Guiding students to reach new heights in careers & lives, while operating from Stratosphere ‚ú®üõ∞Ô∏è'}]}, {'title': 'Smart Medical Cast', 'date': {'start': {'month': 9, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}, 'end': {'month': 2, 'day': None, 'year': 2022}}, 'description': 'Abstract. In this paper, the research project Smart Medical Cast (SMC) is described. The goal of the SMC is to get 
more insight on the healing process of a fractured bone, as well as in the most occurring complications. These 
complications are Muscle atrophy, compartment syndrome, and deep vein thrombosis. These processes are 
monitored by measuring several biomarkers: blood pressure, bone density, blood flow, blood Oxygen saturation, 
muscle activity, cast pressure, and skin temperature. All the biomarkers, except bone density, have been tested in a 
prototype on a healthy person which proved its viability. Combined with the business case, it is shown that there is 
a high potential for further development of the SMC, but there needs to be a more specific patient group to focus on 
in further development.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': ' Jakub ', 'last_name': 'Kylar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Guiding students to reach new heights in careers & lives, while operating from Stratosphere ‚ú®üõ∞Ô∏è'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Lennard', 'last_name': 'Spauwen', 'name': None, 'headline': 'PhD student - UMC Utrecht | Researcher - Smart Systems for Healthy Living'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Tim', 'last_name': 'Heijne', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Ingenieur werktuigbouwkunde | Project ingenieur'}, {'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': 'Mitch', 'last_name': 'Kruijer', 'name': None, 'headline': 'MSc in Next Level Electrical Engineering'}]}, {'title': 'UTV conceptual design (bachelor thesis)', 'date': {'start': {'month': 10, 'day': None, 'year': 2020}, 'end': {'month': 5, 'day': None, 'year': 2021}}, 'description': 'The aim of this research was to conceptualize design of SxS (UTV) vehicle. The thesis was divided into three main parts. The first part focuses on different types of axles used in SxS vehicles. The next part of the research then presents the basic types of drivetrains. This chapter is broken down by component (engine, gearbox, differential, etc.). The last section describes the conceptual design of the actual SxS vehicle using some calculation relationships, but it is not a structural design and this section is more for the purpose of giving an idea.', 'contributors': [{'type': 'standardizedContributor', 'first_name': ' Jakub ', 'last_name': 'Kylar', 'name': None, 'headline': 'Guiding students to reach new heights in careers & lives, while operating from Stratosphere ‚ú®üõ∞Ô∏è'}]}]
